# Institutional Color System for Your Trading Terminal

Here's a complete color architecture used by TC2000, Bloomberg, and professional trading platforms.

---

## The Core Palette Philosophy

Professional terminals use **three distinct color systems** working together: a neutral dark foundation, semantic signal colors, and accent hierarchy. The key insight is that **neutrals do 80% of the work** — color only appears where it carries meaning.

---

## Foundation (Background Layers)

Use exactly 4 depth levels, each 6-8 points lighter than the last:

```
BG-0  #050709   → App shell, outermost container (near-OLED black)
BG-1  #0a0d12   → Primary panels, main content areas
BG-2  #0f1318   → Cards, table rows, input backgrounds
BG-3  #141920   → Hover states, selected rows, elevated elements
BG-4  #1a2030   → Borders and subtle dividers
```

The progression creates natural depth without shadows.

---

## Signal Colors (The Most Important Decisions)

**Never use pure red/green.** Raw #ff0000 and #00ff00 look like amateur stock tickers. Professional platforms use desaturated, slightly warm variants:

```
BULL (Profit / Up / Buy)
  Primary:    #00d4a8   → Teal-green (TC2000's signature)
  Dim:        #1a7a62   → Muted for table backgrounds
  Background: rgba(0,212,168, 0.07) → Subtle row tinting

BEAR (Loss / Down / Sell)
  Primary:    #ff4d6a   → Warm crimson (not pure red)
  Dim:        #7a2030   → Muted for table backgrounds
  Background: rgba(255,77,106, 0.07) → Subtle row tinting

NEUTRAL
  Primary:    #7a94b0   → Blue-grey for unchanged values
  Dim:        #3a4d60   → For secondary data
```

**Why teal-green instead of lime green?** Teal reads as "positive/safe" without the visual aggression of pure green. Bloomberg uses it, TC2000 uses it, most pro platforms use it.

---

## Candle Colors

```
BULL CANDLE
  Body fill:    #00c896   → Brighter than text green for visibility
  Body border:  #009e78   → 20% darker than fill
  Wick:         #009e78

BEAR CANDLE
  Body fill:    #e84060   → Slightly muted from signal red
  Body border:  #b83050   → 20% darker
  Wick:         #b83050

DOJI / Neutral candle: #5a7090
```

For **volume bars**, use the same colors at 55% opacity — this is standard across all professional platforms and visually connects price and volume without competing.

---

## Text Hierarchy

Four levels, strictly enforced:

```
T-0  #e8f0ff   → Primary values: prices, P&L amounts, symbol names
T-1  #a8bcd4   → Secondary: column headers, labels, timestamps
T-2  #5a7090   → Tertiary: muted metadata, axis labels
T-3  #2a3a50   → Quaternary: disabled states, placeholder text
```

The rule: **data that changes gets T-0. Labels that describe it get T-1 or T-2.**

---

## Accent Colors (Functional, Not Decorative)

```
CYAN    #00d4ff   → Live price ray, selected elements, focus rings
AMBER   #f59e0b   → Alerts, warnings, pending orders, ATM strike
PURPLE  #a78bfa   → RSI, indicator overlays
BLUE    #3b82f6   → VWAP, EMA200, informational states
```

Each accent maps to exactly one function. Never reuse amber for something other than alerts.

---

## P&L and Position Colors

```
Open profit:   #00d4a8 with #0a2520 background tint
Open loss:     #ff4d6a with #200a10 background tint
Flat/zero:     #7a94b0 plain, no background tint
Realized gain: #00d4a8 bold
Realized loss: #ff4d6a bold
```

The background tint on table rows is critical — it lets traders read positions at a glance without reading numbers.

---

## Scanner / Watchlist Change Column

```
+3% or more:    #00d4a8 + background rgba(0,212,168,0.12)
+1% to +3%:     #22c4a0 + background rgba(34,196,160,0.07)
-0.5% to +1%:   #7a94b0 plain
-1% to -0.5%:   #e87060 + background rgba(232,112,96,0.07)
-3% or less:    #ff4d6a + background rgba(255,77,106,0.12)
```

This **heat-map gradient** approach is used by every institutional scanner. The color intensity communicates magnitude before the trader reads the number.

